Came to website looking specifically for a riblet recipe. I found and printed this out only to find, once I was set up to prepare the dish, that the riblets were just used for making the sauce. No. no. no. We don't waste anything. The recipe does not state what to do with the riblets after they are sauted. Will not make it again.

Rating: 3
I used olive oil instead of veg oil, diced bacon instead of pork riblets, just chicken broth, a mixed-berry jelly and no corn starch. I also added shallots and whole garlic.

Rating: 3
I just made two chops so I skipped the riblet step and instead cooked the chops as in the recipe, and used the pan I cooked them in to make the sauce. I did not have current jelly on hand so I used currents and a dash of sugar. I used a combo of chix stock and veal demi. No cornstarch thickening needed. Sides of mashed Roquefort potatoes w/Port carmelized onions and green beans made a nice home cooked meal with a gourmet twist.

Rating: 3
I halved the recipe and made the sauce from leftover pork broth I wanted to use. I served the reduced sauce on a plate with pork chops I'd cooked in an iron skillet with a small amount of oil. I did not thicken the sauce with cornstarch. The sauce was scrumptious--a definite do-again. I served mashed Yukon Gold potatoes and Napa cabbage slaw.

Rating: 4
